Inheritance

1. Similar to Inheritance in Life.
2. Child inherits attributes and behaviours from Parent.
3. Inheritance is a way to create a Class from existing Class.
4. The Derived / Child / Sub class inherits some attributes and behaviours from 
Base / Parent / Super Class, and may have more specialised attributes and behaviours.

When do we use Inheritance?

1. After grasping the definition, the pivotal question arises: "When do we use inheritance?"
2. Use inheritance whenever an IS-A relationship is identified between objects.
3. Inheritance is applied where objects exhibit a hierarchical relationship, signifying a specialized-generalized connection.
4. Do not Reinvent the Wheel.

Protected Members

1. Members declared protected are accessible within class itself & to its derived class.

2. The protected access modifier serves two primary purposes:

   1. Encapsulation:
      Like the private access modifier, protected provides a level of
      encapsulation, ensuring that certain class members are not directly
      accessible from outside the class. This promotes data hiding and
      prevents external code from modifying or accessing sensitive data
      directly.

   2. Inheritance:
      Unlike private, protected members can be inherited by derived classes.
      This means that subclasses have limited access to these members,
      allowing them to build upon the base class's functionality while
      maintaining some level of data integrity and control.


| Base Class | Derived Class (Private Mode) | Derived Class (Protected Mode) | Derived Class (Public Mode) |
|------------|-----------------------------|-------------------------------|----------------------------|
| Private    | Not Inherited              | Not Inherited                | Not Inherited             |
| Protected  | Private                    | Protected                    | Protected                 |
| Public     | Private                    | Protected                    | Public                    |




# Types of Inheritance

## 1. Single Inheritance

```text
      ClassA
         ▲
         │
      ClassB
```

---

## 2. Multilevel Inheritance

```text
      ClassA
         ▲
         │
      ClassB
         ▲
         │
      ClassC
```

---

## 3. Hierarchical Inheritance

```text
           ClassA
          ▲     ▲
         /       \
        /         \
   ClassB       ClassC
```

---

## 4. Multiple Inheritance

```text
      ClassA      ClassB
         ▲          ▲
          \        /
           \      /
            \    /
            ClassC
```

---

## 5. Hybrid Inheritance

```text
             ClassA
            ▲     ▲
           /       \
          /         \
     ClassB       ClassC
           ▲       ▲
            \     /
             \   /
             ClassD
```

---

## Quick Revision

```text
Single       : One Parent → One Child

Multilevel   : Grandparent → Parent → Child

Hierarchical : One Parent → Multiple Children

Multiple     : Multiple Parents → One Child

Hybrid       : Combination of Multiple Types
```


#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// ================= BASE CLASS =================

class Vehicle {

protected:
    string name;
    string model;
    int noOfTyres;

public:

    Vehicle(string name, string model, int noOfTyres) {

        cout << "Vehicle Constructor Called" << endl;

        this->name = name;
        this->model = model;
        this->noOfTyres = noOfTyres;
    }

    void startEngine() {
        cout << name << " Engine Started" << endl;
    }

    void stopEngine() {
        cout << name << " Engine Stopped" << endl;
    }

    void showVehicleInfo() {

        cout << "\nVehicle Information" << endl;

        cout << "Name      : " << name << endl;
        cout << "Model     : " << model << endl;
        cout << "Tyres     : " << noOfTyres << endl;
    }

    ~Vehicle() {
        cout << "Vehicle Destructor Called" << endl;
    }
};

// ================= SINGLE INHERITANCE =================

class Car : public Vehicle {

protected:
    int noOfDoors;

public:

    Car(string name,
        string model,
        int noOfTyres,
        int noOfDoors)

        : Vehicle(name, model, noOfTyres)
    {
        cout << "Car Constructor Called" << endl;

        this->noOfDoors = noOfDoors;
    }

    void showCarInfo() {

        showVehicleInfo();

        cout << "Doors     : "
             << noOfDoors << endl;
    }

    void startEngine() {

        cout << "Car Specific Engine Start" << endl;
    }

    ~Car() {
        cout << "Car Destructor Called" << endl;
    }
};

// ================= MULTILEVEL INHERITANCE =================

class SportsCar : public Car {

private:
    int topSpeed;

public:

    SportsCar(string name,
              string model,
              int tyres,
              int doors,
              int topSpeed)

        : Car(name, model, tyres, doors)
    {
        cout << "SportsCar Constructor Called" << endl;

        this->topSpeed = topSpeed;
    }

    void showSportsCarInfo() {

        showCarInfo();

        cout << "Top Speed : "
             << topSpeed << endl;
    }

    ~SportsCar() {
        cout << "SportsCar Destructor Called" << endl;
    }
};

// ================= HIERARCHICAL INHERITANCE =================

class Bike : public Vehicle {

private:
    bool hasABS;

public:

    Bike(string name,
         string model,
         int tyres,
         bool hasABS)

        : Vehicle(name, model, tyres)
    {
        cout << "Bike Constructor Called" << endl;

        this->hasABS = hasABS;
    }

    void showBikeInfo() {

        showVehicleInfo();

        cout << "ABS       : "
             << (hasABS ? "Yes" : "No")
             << endl;
    }

    ~Bike() {
        cout << "Bike Destructor Called" << endl;
    }
};

int main() {

    cout << "=========== SPORTS CAR ===========" << endl;

    SportsCar sc(
        "Ferrari",
        "SF90",
        4,
        2,
        340
    );

    cout << endl;

    sc.showSportsCarInfo();

    cout << endl;

    sc.startEngine();           // Child Version

    cout << endl;

    sc.Vehicle::startEngine();  // Parent Version

    cout << endl;

    cout << "=========== BIKE ===========" << endl;

    Bike b(
        "Yamaha",
        "R15",
        2,
        true
    );

    cout << endl;

    b.showBikeInfo();

    cout << endl;

    return 0;
}


